{"id":"d=origam-topic-4085//p=88dfcbf6631e40ff915798d1c3c13e3f","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4085"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["e44572b11ae74abf95317ba560c7f2ee"],"__file_part":["279540514ca14399b35494ff92a5ffb6"],"__part_n":["4"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"category":["docs"],"categoryId":["8"],"topicId":["4085"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-create-sequential-workflows/4085"],"title":["How to create Sequential Workflows"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" \n   Workflow parameter \n Now we need to create a new parameter (context store reference) and bind it with that context store containing the Id of the record we want to work with: \n          image  408\u00D7268 29.1 KB         \n   XPath based transformation \n Once we have the Id stored in the parameter, we can use it to update the record data. Instead of XSL transformation we will use here a simple XPath based update that is suitable for one field value change. To do that use the  (Task) Update context by Xpath  task type in the transformation step: \n          Update context by XPath task type  556\u00D7412 58.7 KB         \n The  Input  value in this case will be taken from a constant using the XSLT custom function  GetConstant  and put to the  Output  \u2013 field ( FieldName ) and context store ( OutputContextStore ). \n   Additional settings \n The data structure reference in the data load task (step 100_\u2026) uses a filter set \u2013  Method  ( GetById ) you need to create first. That filter set contains just the default filter related to the entity Id ( GetId ). \n          Data structure filter set setting  351\u00D7265 27.4 KB         \n   Workflow overview \n The complete load/transform/save workflow then may look like this: \n          Complete workflow in model browser  268\u00D7526 50.7 KB         \n\n---\n\n@vikter (2026-04-09 07:29:20Z):\n   EXAMPLE 2: Workflow with for-each loop and call of another workflow \n The following workflow is provided here to demonstrate the looping mechanism and the ability to call one workflow from another. \n Here is what the entire workflow looks like: \n          Workflow with loop  928\u00D7693 46.6 KB         \n   For-each loop \n The for-each command \u2013  (Block) For-each  \u2013 is used for the loop here. It executes a sequence for each occurrence of a specific element in the data; in this example, individual elements in  ROOT/services  ( IteratorXPath  property). That is, for each record there, the entire Load / Transform / Store sequence listed in steps 0100 through 0300 is performed. \n          For-each block  340\u00D7312 45.5 KB         \n          Block settings  458\u00D7302 49 KB         \n   Context Store of the Loop \n It is also worth noting that this loop first retrieves data from the \u201Cexternal\u201D context store  InputData  and then uses its own \u201Cinternal\u201D context store, named  Allotment , during its execution. This context store is therefore intended only for this specific block. \n   Calling Another Workflow \n In step 0400, the workflow calls another workflow, which is a  Workflow call (Task)  type, and subsequently passes the necessary data to it via the  OutputContextStore . The output has no further use within this workflow, so the  Output Method  is set to  Ignore . \n          Workflow call task  571\u00D7345 54.7 KB         \n   Workflow overview \n Here is how the workflow may look like in the model browser: \n          Workflow in model browser  290\u00D7476 56.4 KB","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-04-29T00:22:50"},"vector":[-0.028586326,0.02009946,-0.0590874,0.0545722,-0.010340126,-0.01603592,-0.010994981,0.01152864,0.022101346,-0.010629606,-0.006411316,-0.015134953,0.014609335,0.0077348268,0.032213572,0.013645749,-0.024448715,0.023010056,0.050808292,-0.0092396205,-0.023535741,0.011629977,0.009095801,0.001